<subsection xml:id="subsec-perimeter-and-length">
  <title>Perimeter and length</title>

  <introduction>
    <definition xml:id="def-">
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>\textbf{Perimeter}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol marker="a.">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        The perimeter of a shape is the total distance around its edges.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        To find the perimeter, you add the lengths of all the sides of the shape.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Example:
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        For a rectangle with length 6 cm and width 4 cm:
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <md>
                            <mrow>\text{Perimeter}= \amp 2 \times (6+4) </mrow>
                            <mrow>= \amp 20 \,cm </mrow>
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>\textbf{Length}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol marker="a.">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Length usually refers to how long an object is from end to end.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        In a rectangle, the longer side is often called the
                        length, while the shorter is called the width.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Itâ€™s a one-dimensional measure (just one side), not a total like perimeter.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <p>
          <term>Note</term>
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>\text{Length} = </m> one side (e.g., <m>6\, cm</m>)
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>\text{Perimeter} = </m> all sides added together (e.g., <m>20 \,cm </m>for a rectangle)
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
      
  </introduction>
  

